[3] Cholera - West Africa
Date: Thu, 15 Sep 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and The Times (Monrovia) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200509150347.html>

Several West African Countries, including Liberia, Guinea,
Mauritania, Guinea Bissau, and Burkina Faso are said to be faced with
cholera outbreaks. The latest information comes as the Belgium-based
medical group Medecins sans Frontieres sent more staff and medical
supplies in response to the outbreak.
After an initial assessment in Guinea Bissau, where the epidemic is
expanding rapidly, MSF has sent a charter plane with more than 70
tons of medical and logistical supplies. MSF also observed that a
large number of affected patients are from the capital cities of [the
above listed] countries.
MSF said the Antonov 124 flight left from Ostende Airport in Belgium
with drugs, including cholera kits to treat 3000 people, first aid
kits, 2400 meters of plastic sheeting, 12 dispensary tents to set up
cholera treatment centers, water tanks, 1200 jerry cans and spraying
equipment.
"MSF is increasing its response capacity to face the cholera outbreak
all over West Africa," says Stephen Goetghebuer, Operational
Coordinator for this region in Brussels.
Mr. Goetghebuer noted that they treated 282 patients in Burkina Faso
and 2337 severe cases, plus 7291 suspected infections were treated in
Liberia, particularly Monrovia.
The MSF is quoted as saying that in Conakry, Guinea, they have set up
3 treatment centers and given support to another 2, while in
Mauritania, they treated over 1000 people thus far.
"Now we will also open cholera centers in Guinea Bissau. In 2 days we
hope to reach Kachek Island in Guinea, Conakry, from which it is very
hard to get information because radio contacts are unreliable.
Overall, our figures show that the number of cases continues to
increase across many countries in West Africa."
--
