[5] Cholera - Nigeria (Adamawa)
Date: Mon, 12 Sep 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Daily Independent [edited]
<http://www.independentng.com/news/nnsep120526.htm>

No fewer than 10 persons have been reported dead following a fresh
outbreak of cholera in the Chikila district of Guyuk Local Government
Area of Adamawa State. This has brought the death toll in the state
to 28 within a month. In Aug 2005, the cholera epidemic ravaged 3
local government areas of the state, where no fewer than 18 persons
were confirmed dead.
Guyuk South Development Area Administrator, Lazarus Gugu, who broke
the news in Yola, the state capital, blamed the outbreak on poor
sanitary conditions and unhealthy practices among the people. Gugu,
who donated drugs, also said 5 persons died in hospital while others
died at home, adding that several others were in various hospitals
receiving treatment.
It was also gathered that the number of casualties could be higher,
as the epidemic is already spreading to neighboring communities
around the state.
Gugu advised the people to ensure good sanitary habits to check the
spread of the epidemic, adding that the state government would do its
best to assist the victims. He organized sanitation exercises for
the people and educated them on the need to always insist on good
drinking water, toilet facilities and clean cooking environment.
[Byline: Sule Lazarus]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
